They will streamline ops in Singapore and Mexico and likely supply the raw wafers from China which is allowed as not finished product. Hence Maxeon with the tail wind of these tariffs may be at the premium end of price but may well be profitable eventually. So, my best guess is this is a small investment opportunity to hold for a few years. And don't forget that the US and Europe must go massively renewable if only to power all the AI data centers that will require 10% of total power generation. Quite a tail wind. Earning Report! Here is a word on profit, for those that do not understand. When a company makes a dollar, part of it goes to the management, part to the employees, part to the maintenance, part to the materials, part to other minor things, after that is profit. In this case however those profits are also going into expansion and R&D thus making "profits" smaller, but growth and development are important, especially in an industry as competitive as solar. So quite simply, you must look at the whole picture, not just the number at the bottom of the sheet.

After the Record Date, every 100 Existing Shares (including treasury shares) registered in the name of each Shareholder as at the Record Date will be consolidated into one (1) Consolidated Share, fractional entitlements to be disregarded. Each Consolidated Share will rank pari passu in all respects with each other, except that the Consolidated Shares which are to be held as treasury shares will be subject to the provisions of the Companies Act on treasury shares. Shareholders holding less than 100 Existing Shares as at the Record Date will not be entitled to any Consolidated Shares and will no longer be Shareholders upon completion of the Proposed Share Consolidation (the "Affected Shareholders").
